The Unified FFI Pattern: How I Shipped One Rust Binary to Python, Node.js, and PHP Without Compiling on the Client

6 min read
Just now

--

How I designed PardoX’s binding architecture to get absolute performance parity with zero external dependencies.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Introduction
While building PardoX, my columnar data processing engine, I ran into a classic but intimidating software engineering dilemma: how do you bring Rust’s extreme performance to developers in their everyday environments? Data scientists live in Python; high-throughput backend engineers live in Node.js; and a massive chunk of the web still runs on PHP.
My goal was absolute parity. I didn’t want the PHP or JavaScript user to get a “slower” or “stripped-down” version of the engine, and I didn’t want to force anyone to set up complex native compilation toolchains on their production servers.
The industry’s traditional answer is to build ecosystem-specific wrappers: PyO3 for a native Python module, NAPI-RS to compile a Node.js addon, hand-rolled C extensions for PHP. I thought it through and ruled it out fast: three separate binding codebases, three independent cross-compilation matrices, and a titanic synchronization effort every time I add a function to the core.
Instead, I built something simpler and, I think, more elegant: the Unified FFI Pattern. I compile the Rust core as a single C shared library (cdylib) and design ultra-thin wrappers in each host language that load that binary dynamically at runtime.
In this article I’ll walk you through how I thought about this architecture, what the pattern looks like in Python, Node.js, and PHP, and the lessons I learned about cross-language memory management and preventing segmentation faults. I won’t be walking through PardoX’s internal source line by line — that lives in the official docs at pardox.io — but I will show you the pattern itself, with representative examples of how I approached each layer.
Section 1: The Rust Bridge — Building a Unified C-ABI
For any programming language to talk to Rust without a language-specific bridge, everyone has to communicate in the one language every runtime understands natively: the C Application Binary Interface (C-ABI).
In Rust, that means stripping away the compiler’s high-level abstractions and exposing clean functions with #[no_mangle] and the pub extern "C" calling convention. The underlying challenge is that Rust's type system — lifetimes, ownership, generics — doesn't translate directly to C. How do you hand a complex structure like my columnar block manager across that boundary?

