The solution I used is the opaque pointer pattern: the core never exposes its internal structure to the outside. It allocates the object on the heap and hands the host language an untyped pointer. Here’s, broadly, how I design every exposed function:
use std::os::raw::c_char;// Opaque pointer: the host doesn't know what's inside, it just holds onto it
pub struct HyperBlockManager { /* ...internal, never exposed... */ }
#[no_mangle]
pub unsafe extern "C" fn pardox_groupby_agg(
mgr_ptr: *const HyperBlockManager,
group_cols_json: *const c_char,
agg_json: *const c_char,
) -> *mut HyperBlockManager {
if mgr_ptr.is_null() || group_cols_json.is_null() || agg_json.is_null() {
return std::ptr::null_mut();
}
let mgr = &*mgr_ptr;
// Complex parameters travel as plain JSON - this avoids designing
// a separate struct ABI for every single operation
match mgr.groupby_agg_from_json(group_cols_json, agg_json) {
Ok(result) => Box::into_raw(Box::new(result)),
Err(_) => std::ptr::null_mut(),
}
}
The core idea: the host receives opaque pointers and plain text strings (often JSON, so I don’t have to design a different struct ABI for every operation). Rust does the heavy lifting internally with Rayon and SIMD, then hands back a new opaque pointer. The host language never needs to know what’s inside HyperBlockManager — it just needs to hold onto its address for the next call.
Section 2: Consuming the Binary from Python, Node.js, and PHP
Once the binary is compiled (.so on Linux, .dylib on macOS, .dll on Windows), the challenge shifts to the client side. Each language has its own way of dynamically consuming a C-ABI, and I deliberately picked the lowest-friction path in each one.
Python: ctypes, no heavyweights required
I used the standard library’s ctypes. No NumPy as a hard dependency, no C extensions to compile. The loader detects the operating system, loads the matching binary, and explicitly declares the FFI signatures:
import ctypes, sys, ossystem_os = sys.platform
lib_path = resolve_binary_path(system_os) # detects OS/architecture
lib = ctypes.CDLL(lib_path)
# Declare the exact signature Rust expects on the other side
lib.pardox_groupby_agg.argtypes = [ctypes.c_void_p, ctypes.c_char_p, ctypes.c_char_p]
lib.pardox_groupby_agg.restype = ctypes.c_void_p
Node.js: koffi as a replacement for node-gyp
In the JavaScript ecosystem, compiling native modules is usually a headache because of node-gyp. To sidestep that, I used koffi, a fast FFI library that lets you register native functions straight from JavaScript with readable C signatures:
const koffi = require('koffi');
const lib = koffi.load(libPath);const pardoxGroupbyAgg = lib.func(
'void * pardox_groupby_agg(void * mgr, const char * group_cols_json, const char * agg_json)'
);
PHP: breaking barriers with ext-ffi
PHP 8.1 brought native FFI into the core. That opens a huge door: PHP can finally act as a high-performance scripting interface. I generate a C header at load time and hand it to the interpreter:
namespace PardoX\Core;use FFI as PhpFFI;
final class Engine
{
public static function load(): PhpFFI
{
$header = "
typedef void HyperBlockManager;
void * pardox_groupby_agg(void * mgr, const char * group_cols_json, const char * agg_json);
";
return PhpFFI::cdef($header, self::libraryPath());
}
}
Thanks to this approach, all three SDKs end up sharing exactly the same binary. If I improve performance in Rust, all three languages benefit instantly — without recompiling a single line on the client side.
Section 3: The Big FFI Challenge — Memory and Segfaults
The Unified FFI Pattern buys portability and low maintenance, but it isn’t free. The biggest danger of crossing the FFI boundary is that you leave Rust’s borrow-checker safety net behind.
When I hand a Rust pointer to Python, Node.js, or PHP, those languages’ garbage collectors have no idea what’s behind that memory address. If the engine creates a structure on the heap, that memory exists until Rust explicitly frees it. That opens up two fronts: memory leaks and dangling pointers that end in a segmentation fault.
To avoid disasters, I adopted a strict explicit manual release protocol: every heap constructor has a matching FFI destructor in the core.
#[no_mangle]
pub unsafe extern "C" fn pardox_free_manager(mgr_ptr: *mut HyperBlockManager) {
if !mgr_ptr.is_null() {
// Reclaim ownership of the pointer so Rust frees it
drop(Box::from_raw(mgr_ptr));
}
}In the wrappers, that lifecycle is hidden inside high-level objects. In Python and JavaScript, for example, DataFrames make sure to release the native pointer once they’re done being used:
class DataFrame {
constructor(ptr) { this.ptr = ptr; }free() {
if (this.ptr) {
lib.pardox_free_manager(this.ptr);
this.ptr = null;
}
}
}
Another challenge that took me a while to get right was handling char*. When Rust returns text to the host — a JSON payload, say — it can't just hand back a native Rust string as-is. It builds a CString and releases it with into_raw(). The host reads those bytes into its own memory, and then has to call back into Rust (pardox_free_string) to free that pointer. Forget that step, and you've got a silent leak that will come back to bite you in production.
Final Thoughts
Designing PardoX around the Unified FFI Pattern changed how I think about systems software development. The conventional wisdom says that to support a language you need to integrate deeply into its native ecosystem. But the maturity of modern foreign function interfaces — koffi in Node, native FFI in PHP, ctypes in Python — proves that the C-ABI is still the interoperability superhighway.
By centralizing all the heavy logic inside the Rust core, I got a low-resource PHP server to run parallel analytical filtering at the same speed as a Python app or a Node.js microservice.
The cost is strict memory discipline and careful design of the binary boundaries. In exchange, you get enormous distribution simplicity: one shared library for every language. For anyone chasing high-performance, portable software, Rust plus dynamic FFI is no longer an exotic choice — it’s the gold standard.
If you want to see the full architecture, API reference, and real benchmarks, it’s all documented at pardox.io.
See you in the compiler.
